# D_Ze — Ze-Дискордантность

**Ze-discordance: conflict between Ze-subsystems with different world models as a universal measure of disease, aging, and evolutionary complexity.**

---

## 1. Hypothesis

In any system composed of multiple Ze-subsystems (tissues, organs, components), **conflict arises when subsystems have different Ze-parameters** (v, τ, Z). This conflict — measured by D_Ze — is the information-theoretic equivalent of disease in both living and non-living systems.

### Key hypotheses:

- **H₁ (Ze-discordance):** D_Ze > 0.1 between two subsystems creates measurable excess T-events (Ze-friction, F_Ze > 0.05) at their boundary.
- **H₂ (biological aging):** Biological age = Σ w_ij · D_Ze(i, j). Higher D_Ze → faster aging.
- **H₃ (brain learning):** D_Ze between hippocampus (v=0.32) and neocortex (v=0.10) ≈ 0.22 is the mechanism of learning — T-events at zone boundaries = new connections.
- **H₄ (evolution):** D_Ze increases with evolutionary complexity: unicellular colonies (D_Ze < 0.05) < plants (0.05–0.10) < Metazoa (0.10–0.30). True somatic differentiation creates internal Ze-conflict.

**Null hypothesis (H₀):** D_Ze does not correlate with any measurable biological or physical outcome — all Ze-subsystems are independent and their parameter differences are irrelevant.

---

## 2. Core Definition

**D_Ze** (Ze-discordance) is the normalized Manhattan distance between Ze-parameter vectors of two subsystems:

\[
D_{\text{Ze}}(A, B) = \frac{|\Delta v| + |\Delta \tau| + |\Delta Z|}{3}
\]

Where:
- Δv = v_A − v_B (Ze-velocity difference)
- Δτ = τ_A − τ_B (Ze-complexity difference)
- ΔZ = Z_A − Z_B (Ze-index difference)

**Ze-friction** (F_Ze) — the rate of excess T-events at the subsystem boundary:

\[
F_{\text{Ze}} = D_{\text{Ze}} \cdot \frac{v_1 + v_2}{2}
\]

---

## 3. Disease Thresholds

| State | D_Ze | F_Ze | Observable |
|-------|:----:|:----:|------------|
| **Health** | < 0.1 | < 0.05 | T/S balance preserved; system stable |
| **Ze-friction** | 0.1–0.3 | 0.05–0.15 | Excess T-events at boundary; noisy operation |
| **Ze-conflict** | 0.3–0.5 | 0.15–0.3 | Macroscopic T-cascades; visible dysfunction |
| **Ze-desynchronosis** | > 0.5 | > 0.3 | Irreversible degradation; aging / breakdown |

---

## 4. D_Ze in Hierarchical Thermodynamics

D_Ze maps directly to the difference in entropy production rates between hierarchical levels:

| Ze parameter | Thermodynamic equivalent | Meaning |
|--------------|-------------------------|---------|
| τ = H/log₂(N) | S/k_B | Normalized entropy of event stream |
| v = (N_T−N_S)/N | σΔt/k_B | Entropy production rate (in T/S units) |
| Z = N_T/N | exp(σΔt/k_B) / (1+exp(σΔt/k_B)) | Forward/backward ratio in Fluctuation Theorem |

**Fluctuation Theorem** (Evans & Searles, 1994) in Ze-form:

\[
\frac{P(T)}{P(S)} = \exp(v \cdot N)
\]

**Hierarchical FT:** Each level k has its own FT with characteristic time Δt_k. D_Ze > 0 means P_k(T)/P_k(S) ≠ P_l(T)/P_l(S) — the two levels make contradictory predictions about the same event. This is the thermodynamic definition of disease.

---

## 5. Tissue D_Ze

### 5.1. Half-Restoration Period and Cytogenetic Status

Every cell has a **cytogenetic status** — position on the axis from totipotency to terminal differentiation. This determines:

- **Half-restoration period** (T_½) — planned cell renewal in homeostasis
- **Ze-velocity** (v) — lower with deeper differentiation
- **Ze-complexity** (τ) — higher with deeper differentiation

Even cells of the same type differ: a stem hepatocyte (T_½ ~3–6mo, v=0.32) vs a terminally differentiated hepatocyte (T_½ ~2+yr, v=0.25) are different Ze-subsystems.

### 5.2. Tissue D_Ze Table

| Tissue pair | v₁ | v₂ | D_Ze | Interpretation |
|-------------|:--:|:--:|:----:|---------------|
| Hippocampus – neocortex | 0.32 | 0.10 | **0.22** | Brain internal conflict = learning |
| Gut epithelium – bone | 0.40 | 0.25 | **0.25** | Max conflict = chronic inflammation |
| Gut epithelium – skin | 0.40 | 0.35 | 0.08 | Fast renewal, low conflict |
| Epithelium – connective tissue | 0.40 | 0.28 | **0.20** | Chronic inflammation boundary |
| Blood – neocortex | 0.33 | 0.10 | **0.22** | BBB = barrier between Ze-worlds |
| Hippocampus – cerebellum | 0.32 | 0.08 | **0.24** | Plasticity vs automatisms |

### 5.3. The Brain as an Ensemble of Ze-Subsystems

| Brain zone | v | τ | T_½ | World model |
|------------|:--:|:--:|:---:|-------------|
| Olfactory bulb | 0.34 | 0.31 | 6–12 mo | Short, sensory |
| Hippocampus | 0.32 | 0.32 | 1–2 yr | Learning, memory formation |
| Striatum | 0.18 | 0.40 | 30–50 yr | Motor skills, slow update |
| Neocortex | 0.10 | 0.45 | ~100+ yr | Long-term memory |
| Cerebellum | 0.08 | 0.47 | No renewal | Coordination, automatisms |

**D_Ze(hippocampus, neocortex) ≈ 0.22** — significant internal conflict. Hypothesis: this is the **mechanism of learning**: T-events at zone boundaries create new connections. Brain diseases (dementia, schizophrenia) = disruption of this Ze-balance.

---

## 6. Evolutionary Hierarchy of Ze-Differentiation

| Level | Organisms | Irreversible differentiation | Characteristic D_Ze | Price |
|:-----:|-----------|:---------------------------:|:-------------------:|-------|
| **0** | Bacteria, Archaea | None | 0 | No multicellularity |
| **1** | Colonial unicellular (Dictyostelium, Volvox) | Germ + somatic cells only. Rest — modulation | < 0.05 | Primitive分工 |
| **2** | Plants (Plantae) | Germ cells only. Somatic modulation with dedifferentiation | 0.05–0.10 | Moderate complexity |
| **3** | Invertebrates (Metazoa) | Partial somatic irreversible differentiation | 0.10–0.20 | Organ systems |
| **4** | Vertebrates | Full somatic differentiation + adaptive immune system | 0.15–0.25 | Advanced organs |
| **5** | Mammals with brain | Maximal differentiation + neural heterogeneity | 0.20–0.30 | Consciousness, but high D_Ze |

**Key insight:** Evolution of multicellularity with irreversible somatic differentiation **created internal Ze-conflicts**. High organization = high D_Ze = aging. This is the thermodynamic price of complexity.

---

## 7. Biological Age Formula

\[
\text{Biological Age} = \sum_{i<j} w_{ij} \cdot D_{\text{Ze}}(i, j)
\]

Where w_{ij} are weights proportional to the contact area between tissues i and j.

**Prediction:** D_Ze computed from biopsy-derived Ze-parameters correlates with chronological age and predicts age-related pathologies before clinical manifestation.

---

## 8. Relation to Ze-Hierarchy Experiment

The expanded test matrix (F1–F4, G) in Ze-Hierarchy directly tests D_Ze:

| Test | What it does | D_Ze analog | Prediction |
|------|-------------|-------------|:----------:|
| F1 | Recharge old bots to 5V | τ_micro irreversibility | HI > 0.5 |
| F2 | Replace ESP32 on old bots | "Tissue transplant" | HI drops if age = silicon |
| F3 | Mixed-age assembly | **High D_Ze organism** | HI chaotic / collapses |
| F4 | Old vs new silicon (same τ_create) | τ_atom effect | HI > 0.5 |
| G | All components same year | Zero D_Ze control | HI ≈ 0.5 |

**F3 directly models a "sick" organism** where D_Ze > 0.3 between components → chaotic behavior → hierarchy collapse.

---

## 9. Experimental Protocols

### 9.1. In Vitro (Tissue Boundary)
1. Co-culture two cell types with different T_½ (e.g., epithelium T_½=5d + fibroblasts T_½=6mo)
2. Measure T-event frequency at boundary (Ca²⁺ imaging: T = spike above threshold)
3. Compute v₁, v₂, D_Ze from event streams
4. Expected: D_Ze > 0.2 → chronic T-cascades → inflammation markers (IL-6, TNF-α)

### 9.2. In Vivo (Biopsy)
1. Biopsy from multiple tissues (liver, skin, blood, hippocampus)
2. Single-cell RNA-seq → infer T_½ from Ki67, H2B-GFP dilution
3. Compute v, τ, Z per tissue
4. Compute D_Ze matrix → correlate with chronological age

### 9.3. Evolutionary Survey
1. Compare D_Ze across species: Dictyostelium → Arabidopsis → Drosophila → Mus → Homo
2. Predict: D_Ze increases with differentiation complexity

---

## 10. Falsifiability

| Condition | Verdict |
|-----------|---------|
| D_Ze does not correlate with any measurable outcome (in vitro, in vivo, evolution) | ❌ D_Ze concept rejected |
| D_Ze correlates with inflammation markers in vitro | ✅ Validates tissue D_Ze |
| D_Ze correlates with biological age in vivo | ✅ Validates aging formula |
| D_Ze increases across evolutionary levels | ✅ Validates evolutionary hierarchy |
| F3 test (mixed-age assembly) shows HI ≈ 0.5 | ❌ D_Ze ≠ chaotic assembly |

---

## 11. Related Works

| Work | Finding | Our difference |
|------|---------|----------------|
| Hierarchical thermodynamics (Prigogine, 1978) | Levels have different relaxation times | We map relaxation time → v → D_Ze |
| Fluctuation Theorem (Evans & Searles, 1994) | P(+σ)/P(−σ) = exp(σΔt/k_B) | We rewrite as P(T)/P(S) = exp(v·N) |
| Hayflick limit (1965) | Replicative senescence in cell culture | Cytogenetic status → v → T_½ |
| Aging as entropy (Yates, 2002) | Entropy production increases with age | D_Ze = entropy production mismatch between tissues |
| Neurogenesis (Eriksson, 1998) | Adult neurogenesis in hippocampus | Hippocampus (v=0.32) vs neocortex (v=0.10) = brain D_Ze |
| Garnier et al. (2013, PLOS ONE) | Age doesn't affect hierarchy in ant swarms | We measure D_Ze directly, not just age |

